disciplines of differential topology, differential and algebraic geometry, cohomology, and fiber bundle theory. As such, it is a fundamental and an essential tool in the study of differentiable manifolds.In this volume, the authors provide a thorough introduction to characteristic classes, with detailed studies of Stiefel-Whitney classes, Chern classes, Pontrjagin classes, and the Euler class. Three appendices cover the basics of cohomology theory and the differential forms approach to characteristic classes, and provide an account of Bernoulli numbers.Based on lecture notes of John Milnor, which first appeared at Princeton University in 1957 and have been widely studied by graduate students of topology ever since, this published version has been completely revised and corrected.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCharacteristic classes. 7aMATHEMATICS / Topology.2bisacsh  aAdditive group.  aAxiom.  aBasis (linear algebra).  aBoundary (topology).  aBundle map.  aCW complex.  aCanonical map.  aCap product.  aCartesian product.  aCharacteristic class.  aCharles Ehresmann.  aChern class.  aClassifying space.  aCoefficient.  aCohomology ring.  aCohomology.  aCompact space.  aComplex dimension.  aComplex manifold.  aComplex vector bundle.  aComplexification.  aComputation.  aConformal geometry.  aContinuous function.  aCoordinate space.  aCross product.  aDe Rham cohomology.  aDiffeomorphism.  aDifferentiable manifold.  aDifferential form.  aDifferential operator.  aDimension (vector space).  aDimension.  aDirect sum.  aDirectional derivative.  aEilenberg–Steenrod axioms.  aEmbedding.  aEquivalence class.  aEuler class.  aEuler number.  aExistence theorem.  aExistential quantification.  aExterior (topology).  aFiber bundle.  aFundamental